<subSubSection pageId="7" pageNumber="158" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,1708,2023]" pageId="7" pageNumber="158">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,314,1708,1734]" pageId="7" pageNumber="158">Diagnosis</emphasis>
: A very distinct species based on the narrow face in combination with the single alar sclerite. Similar to 
<taxonomicName authority="Johansson" authorityName="Johansson &amp; Ameri &amp; Riedel &amp; Talebi &amp; Ebrahimi" authorityYear="2021" box="[180,485,1744,1770]" class="Insecta" family="Ichneumonidae" genus="Enicospilus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="7" pageNumber="158" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="peri" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[180,363,1744,1770]" italics="true" pageId="7" pageNumber="158">Enicospilus peri</emphasis>
Johansson
</taxonomicName>
<emphasis bold="true" box="[492,581,1744,1770]" pageId="7" pageNumber="158">
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[492,581,1744,1770]" pageId="7" pageNumber="158" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</emphasis>
, but with narrower face and temples and fewer and stouter flagellomeres.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection lastPageId="8" lastPageNumber="159" pageId="7" pageNumber="158" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="7.[151,1437,1708,2023]" lastBlockId="8.[151,1437,151,393]" lastPageId="8" lastPageNumber="159" pageId="7" pageNumber="158">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,337,1780,1806]" pageId="7" pageNumber="158">Description</emphasis>
: Male unknown. Fore wing length 
<quantity box="[753,839,1780,1807]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.0" pageId="7" pageNumber="158" unit="mm" value="10.0">10 mm</quantity>
. Body length 
<quantity box="[1004,1089,1780,1807]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.5" pageId="7" pageNumber="158" unit="mm" value="15.0">15 mm</quantity>
. Number of flagellomeres 47. Mandible small and strongly twisted with upper tooth about two × as long as lower tooth. First flagellomere quite stout, about 4.0 × as long as apically wide. Mid and preapical flagellomeres stout about 1.2 × as long as wide (
<figureCitation captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1566,1590]" captionTargetBox="[157,1429,237,1542]" captionTargetId="figure-46@7.[157,1429,237,1542]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 4. Enicospilus apocalypticus Johansson sp. nov. holotype ♀ (HMIM). A) Habitus, lateral view; B) head, anterior view; C) head, dorsal view; D) apical flagellomeres; E) alar sclerites; F) hind tarsal claws; G) propodeum, dorsal view. Photos: Niklas Johansson." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5225663" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5225663/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="158">Fig. 4D</figureCitation>
). Face very narrow in anterior view (
<figureCitation box="[603,692,1888,1914]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1566,1590]" captionTargetBox="[157,1429,237,1542]" captionTargetId="figure-46@7.[157,1429,237,1542]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 4. Enicospilus apocalypticus Johansson sp. nov. holotype ♀ (HMIM). A) Habitus, lateral view; B) head, anterior view; C) head, dorsal view; D) apical flagellomeres; E) alar sclerites; F) hind tarsal claws; G) propodeum, dorsal view. Photos: Niklas Johansson." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5225663" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5225663/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="158">Fig. 4B</figureCitation>
). Temples strongly narrowed, in lateral view about 0.2 × the width of compound eye. Lateral ocelli touching inner margin of compound eye (
<figureCitation box="[1006,1097,1924,1950]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1566,1590]" captionTargetBox="[157,1429,237,1542]" captionTargetId="figure-46@7.[157,1429,237,1542]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 4. Enicospilus apocalypticus Johansson sp. nov. holotype ♀ (HMIM). A) Habitus, lateral view; B) head, anterior view; C) head, dorsal view; D) apical flagellomeres; E) alar sclerites; F) hind tarsal claws; G) propodeum, dorsal view. Photos: Niklas Johansson." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5225663" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5225663/files/figure.png" pageId="7" pageNumber="158">Fig. 4C</figureCitation>
). Clypeus flat in lateral view. Mesoscutum strongly polished with very dense irregular puncture. Mesopleuron closely punctate, rugulose with weak transverse striation. Epicnemial carina ventrally complete, sinuate. Scutellum with lateral carinae, its surface polished with dense punctures. Proximal sclerite entirely pigmented, triangular. Central and distal sclerite absent. Propodeum with transverse carina weak, anterior of the carina polished wihout punctures, posterior to the carina entirely transversely reticulate-rugulose (
<figureCitation box="[617,709,223,249]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1566,1590]" captionTargetBox="[157,1429,237,1542]" captionTargetId="figure-46@7.[157,1429,237,1542]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 4. Enicospilus apocalypticus Johansson sp. nov. holotype ♀ (HMIM). A) Habitus, lateral view; B) head, anterior view; C) head, dorsal view; D) apical flagellomeres; E) alar sclerites; F) hind tarsal claws; G) propodeum, dorsal view. Photos: Niklas Johansson." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5225663" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5225663/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="159">Fig. 4G</figureCitation>
). Hind femur narrow, about 8.0 × longer than wide. Hind tarsal claws pectinate (
<figureCitation box="[338,424,259,285]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1566,1590]" captionTargetBox="[157,1429,237,1542]" captionTargetId="figure-46@7.[157,1429,237,1542]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 4. Enicospilus apocalypticus Johansson sp. nov. holotype ♀ (HMIM). A) Habitus, lateral view; B) head, anterior view; C) head, dorsal view; D) apical flagellomeres; E) alar sclerites; F) hind tarsal claws; G) propodeum, dorsal view. Photos: Niklas Johansson." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5225663" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5225663/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="159">Fig. 4F</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="8.[151,1437,151,393]" pageId="8" pageNumber="159">
<emphasis box="[199,345,295,321]" italics="true" pageId="8" pageNumber="159">Colouration:</emphasis>
Uniformly testaceous (
<figureCitation box="[622,717,295,321]" captionStart="FIGURE 4" captionStartId="7.[151,250,1566,1590]" captionTargetBox="[157,1429,237,1542]" captionTargetId="figure-46@7.[157,1429,237,1542]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURE 4. Enicospilus apocalypticus Johansson sp. nov. holotype ♀ (HMIM). A) Habitus, lateral view; B) head, anterior view; C) head, dorsal view; D) apical flagellomeres; E) alar sclerites; F) hind tarsal claws; G) propodeum, dorsal view. Photos: Niklas Johansson." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.5225663" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/5225663/files/figure.png" pageId="8" pageNumber="159">Fig. 4A</figureCitation>
). Inner and outer orbits widely pale. Mandibular teeth black. Ovipositor sheath testaceous, concolourous with the metasomal segments. Forewing veins and pterostigma testaceous.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
